Note : Diamond clarity is a measure of the purity and rarity of the stone, graded by the visibility of these characteristics under 10-power magnification. A stone is graded as flawless if, under 10-power magnification, no inclusions (internal flaws) and no blemishes (external imperfections) are visible.

  • FL diamonds are Flawless
  • IF diamonds are Internally Flawless
  • VVS1 VVS2 : VVS diamonds (1 and 2) are Very, Very Slightly Included
  • VS1 VS2 : VS diamonds (1 and 2) are Very Slightly Included
  • SI1 SI2 : SI diamonds (1 and 2) are Slightly Included
  • I1 I2 I3 : I diamonds (1, 2 and 3) are Imperfect

Source : Tiffany Diamonds

===============================================================================================================

Chart 1 : Distribution of Price Seperate By Clarity

set.seed(33)
ggplot(diamonds %>% sample_n(700), aes(price, fill = clarity)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 13,position = "fill") +
  geom_rug() +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(
    title = "Distribution of Price Seperate By Clarity",
    x = "Price USD",
    y = "Count",
    fill = "Clarity",
    caption = "Datasource : Diamonds Base R"
  )

This chart show the distribution of price seperated by clarity. Black bar code below the chart show the concentration of price.

===============================================================================================================

Chart 2 : Relationship Between Carat and Price Seperate By Cut

set.seed(33)
ggplot(diamonds %>% sample_frac(0.3), aes(carat, price, col = cut)) +
  geom_point(alpha=1) +
  geom_smooth() +
  scale_color_brewer(type="seq", palette=11) +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(
    title = "Relationship Between Carat and Price Seperate By Cut",
    x = "Carat",
    y = "Price USD",
    colour = "Cut",
    caption = "Datasource : Diamonds Base R"
  )

From this chart show a positive relationship between carat and price.

===============================================================================================================

Chart 3 : Relationship Between Depth and Price Seperate By Cut

set.seed(33)
ggplot(diamonds %>% sample_frac(0.3), aes(depth, price, col = cut)) +
  geom_point(size=5, alpha=0.3) +
  facet_wrap(~cut, ncol = 5) +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(
    title = "Relationship Between Depth and Price Seperate By Cut",
    x = "Depth",
    y = "Price USD",
    colour = "Cut",
    caption = "Datasource : Diamonds Base R"
  )

From this chart show a positive relationship between depth and price.

===============================================================================================================

Chart 4 : Relationship Between Clarity and Carat

set.seed(33)
ggplot(diamonds %>% sample_frac(0.3), aes(clarity, carat, col = clarity))+
  geom_boxplot() +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(
    title = "Relationship Between Clarity and Carat",
    x = "Clarity",
    y = "Carat",
    colour = "Clarity",
    caption = "Datasource : Diamonds Base R"
  )

From this box plot show a relationship. Higher carat be tends less clarity.

Chart 5 : Relationship Between Table and Price Seperate By Cut

set.seed(33)
ggplot(diamonds %>% sample_n(800), aes(table, price, col = cut)) +
  geom_point(alpha=0.5) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm") +
  theme_minimal() +
  scale_color_brewer(type = "qual", palette = 7) +
  facet_wrap(~cut) +
  labs(
    title = "Relationship Between Table and Price Seperate By Cut",
    x = "Table",
    y = "Price",
    colour = "Cut",
    caption = "Datasource : Diamonds Base R"
  )

This chart table and price arent related. However when seperate and wrap with column cut will see that some cutting method price and table be related.
